Keith A. Whitmore (born 15 June 1955) is a British politician and current President of the <a href="/wiki/Congress_of_the_Council_of_Europe" title="Congress of the Council of Europe">Congress of the Council of Europe</a>.
Keith Whitmore was born on 15 June 1955 in <a href="/wiki/Manchester" title="Manchester">Manchester</a>, United Kingdom.
Whitmore was first elected to <a href="/wiki/Manchester_City_Council" title="Manchester City Council">Manchester City Council</a> in May 1979 and has remained a member since then. From 1988 to 1997 he was leader of the Manchester Liberal Democrat Group of Councillors. He represents the <a href="/wiki/Levenshulme" title="Levenshulme">Levenshulme</a> ward.
He is Deputy Chairman of the Greater Manchester Integrated Transport Authority and is a Director of Greater Manchester Accessible Transport and the Manchester Museum of Transport.
Whitmore has been a member of the <a href="/wiki/Congress_of_the_Council_of_Europe" title="Congress of the Council of Europe">Congress of the Council of Europe</a> since 1996.
He was elected President of the Congress of Local and Regional Authorities of the Council of Europe on 26 October 2010. Other offices previously held include Chairman of the Institutional Committee of the Congress, Vice-President of the Congress, Chairman of the Congress's Sustainable Development Committee and head of the UK delegation to the Congress.
Within the Council of Europe, Whitmore's party affiliation is with the Independent and Liberal Democrat Group (ILDG), of which he is chairman.
